Predicting ICU duration

Using the ICU cohort mimiciv_icu_cohort.rds you built in Homework 4, develop at least three machine learning approaches (logistic regression with enet regularization, random forest, boosting, SVM, MLP, etc) plus a model stacking approach for predicting whether a patientâs ICU stay will be longer than 2 days. You should use the los_long variable as the outcome. You algorithms can use patient demographic information (gender, age at ICU intime, marital status, race), ICU admission information (first care unit), the last lab measurements before the ICU stay, and first vital measurements during ICU stay as features. You are welcome to use any feature engineering techniques you think are appropriate; but make sure to not use features that are not available at an ICU stayâs intime. For instance, last_careunit cannot be used in your algorithms.

  1. Data preprocessing and feature engineering.

Answer:

We removed features that will not be used in this task. We also converted los_long to a factor variable so it can be used as the outcome variable in the model. We checked the distribution of the outcome variable and found that the data is relatively balanced.

mimiciv_icu_cohort <- readRDS("./mimic_icu_cohort.rds")
# Remove features that will not be used in this task
mimiciv_icu_cohort <- mimiciv_icu_cohort |>
  arrange(subject_id, hadm_id, stay_id) |>
  select(-c(subject_id, hadm_id, stay_id, last_careunit, intime, outtime, 
            admittime, dischtime, deathtime, admit_provider_id, 
            discharge_location, language, edregtime, edouttime, anchor_age,
            anchor_year, anchor_year_group, dod, hospital_expire_flag, 
            admission_type, admission_location, insurance, los))
mimiciv_icu_cohort <- mimiciv_icu_cohort |>
  mutate(los_long = ifelse(los_long == TRUE, 1, 0)) |>
  mutate(los_long = as.factor(los_long))
# create a bar plot of the outcome variable
mimiciv_icu_cohort |>
  ggplot(aes(x = los_long)) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(title = "Distribution of the outcome variable",
       x = "ICU stay longer than 2 days",
       y = "Count")
  1. Partition data into 50% training set and 50% test set. Stratify partitioning according to los_long. For grading purpose, sort the data by subject_id, hadm_id, and stay_id and use the seed 203 for the initial data split. Below is the sample code.

Answer:

Data is split into 50% training set and 50% test set. The split is stratified according to los_long. The data has been sorted in the previous question.

set.seed(203)

data_split <- initial_split(
  mimiciv_icu_cohort, 
  # stratify by los_long
  strata = "los_long", 
  prop = 0.5
  )

  1. Train and tune the models using the training set.

Answer: Three independent machine learning algorithms and one stacked model based on these three algorithms were tested in this section. We tuned parameters of each model on training set with 5 folds cross validation. The best set of parameters were selected based on the AUC score of model in each set of parameter. The entire workflow with the best set of parameters was applied to the test set to evaluate the performance of the model. Feature importance were extracted and reported at the end of each model.

# Define parameters to tune in later steps
rf_mod <- 
  rand_forest(
    mode = "classification",
    mtry = tune(),
    min_n = tune(),
    # tree can be a tuning parameter but it seems like the more trees in the
    # model, the better performance it will be. Therefore, we fix the amount
    # of tree for this task
    trees = 1000
  ) |> 
  set_engine("ranger", importance = "impurity") |>
  set_mode("classification")
rf_mod

  1. Compare model classification performance on the test set. Report both the area under ROC curve and accuracy for each machine learning algorithm and the model stacking. Interpret the results. What are the most important features in predicting long ICU stays? How do the models compare in terms of performance and interpretability?

Answer:

The logistic regression has an AUC of 0.596 and accuracy of 0.575. The random forest has an AUC of 0.639 and accuracy of 0.601. The gradient boosting has an AUC of 0.645 and accuracy of 0.603. The model stacking has an AUC of 0.648 and accuracy of 0.606.

The logistic regression performs the worst in this task. It has the lowest AUC and accuracy. The performance of gradient boosting model is slightly better than that of random forest. The stacked model has the highest AUC and accuracy but it is not significantly better than the gradient boosting model alone.

The three independent models have different ranking for feature importance. Here is the report of the variables with similar importance in each model. Logistic regression selects âheart rateâ and âfirst care unitâ as most important features. Random Forest selects âwhite Blood cellsâ, âhematocritâ, âheart rateâ, ânon invasive blood pressure systolicâ, and âbody temperatureâ as the most important features. Gradient Boosting selects âbody temperatureâ of the patient as the most important feature. Among those features, both logistic regression and random forest agree that âheart rateâ is a very important feature in predicting long ICU stays. Both random forest and gradient boosting agrees that âbody temperatureâ is a very important feature in predicting long ICU stays. The difference of feature importance rank between logistic regression and the other two models are reasonable since logistic regression is a linear model which may not capture the non-linear relationship between the features and the target variable. The difference between random forest and gradient boosting is also reasonable since random forest is an ensemble of decision trees and gradient boosting is a boosting algorithm which builds trees sequentially where each tree tries to correct the errors of the previous tree. Feature importance in random forest is based on how much each feature decreases the impurity in the nodes of the tree, while feature importance in gradient boosting is based on how much in average each feature contributes to the improvement of the model. Different mechanism results in different feature importance rank. Given these backgrounds, I argue that âheart rateâ and âbody temperatureâ are the most important features in predicting long ICU stays since they are selected in two out of three models.

In terms of interpretability, logistic regression is the most interpretable model since it is a linear model but it has the worst performance. Random forest and gradient boosting are less interpretable since they are ensemble models but they have much better performance than the logistic regression. Model stacking is the least interpretable model since it is a combination of multiple models. However, stacked model has the best performance among all models. In this case, the choice of model should be based on the trade-off between performance and interpretability. If the interpretability is more important, logistic regression should be chosen. If the performance is more important, gradient boosting should be chosen. If the trade-off between performance and interpretability is acceptable, random forest should be chosen. If the best performance is required, stacked model should be chosen.
